{"cursor":"26867","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n:\"Scottish Ministers\" redirects here; not to be confused with the pre-1999 use\n:of the term, when it applied to the ministers of the [[Scottish Office]].\n{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Scottish Government Riaghaltas na\nh-Alba |type = Government |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal =Scottish\nGovernment logo.png |seal_width = 150px |seal_caption = Logo of the Scottish\nGovernment |formed = 1999 |preceding2 = |dissolved = |superseding =\n|jurisdiction = Scotland |headquarters = St Andrew's House, Edinburgh, Scotland\n|employees = 17.000 [http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Statistics/Browse/Labour-\nMarket/TrendData Public Sector employment in Scotland (Civil service)]\n|budget = Â£28.6 billion (2013/14) |minister1_name = The Rt. Hon. Alex Salmond,\nMSP |minister1_pfo = First Minister |chief1_name = Sir Peter Housden, KCB\n|chief1_position = Permanent Secretary |child1_agency = |website =\n[http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Home www.scotland.gov.uk] |footnotes = }}\n\nThe 'Scottish Government' (, ) is the executive branch of the devolved\ngovernment of Scotland. It is accountable to the Scottish Parliament.\n\nThe government was established in 1999 as the 'Scottish Executive' under section\n44(1) of the Scotland Act\n1998. [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1998/46/part/II Part II of the\nScotland Act 1998 retrieved from legislation.gov.uk] It was formally\nrenamed in law as the Scottish Government at the beginning of July 2012, when\nsection 12(1) of the Scotland Act 2012 came into force.\n\nThe Scottish Government is led by the First Minister, who selects all the\nremaining Cabinet Secretaries and junior Ministers. The First Minister and the\nCabinet Secretaries constitute the\nCabinet. [http://www.scotland.gov.uk/About/14944 retrieved from\nscotland.gov.uk]\n","linknr":813,"url":"Scottish_Executive","recorded":1362583774,"links":62,"instances":["politician","heraldry","politician","scot